'''Macaquitos''' ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]: '''macaquinhos''') is a [[Spanish Language]] [[racist]] term used occasionally by [[Argentina|Argentine]] fans against [[Brazil|Brazilians]] within the context of the [[Argentina and Brazil football rivalry|football rivalry]] between the two countries. This [[pejorative]] term links the [[Black (people)|black]] and [[mulatto]] origins of many Brazilian football players to [[monkey]]s.

Some claim that the term was first used among the Argentine troops during the [[War of the Triple Alliance]].

The first time the word was quoted was in 1920 after a friendly match that [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] won 3-1. It was again used by Argentine fans in several of the ensuing matches, but fell out of use during the 1940s. In later years, the [[yellow press]] has used the expression to fan the flames of rivalry.

Argentina's [[Diario Olé]] ran the controversial headline ''Que vengan los macacos'' ("bring the monkeys on"), when Argentina's rival for the final match of the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Olympics]] was to be decided between [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] and [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]]. The headline was criticised both in Argentina and Brazil. Nigeria eventually won the match, and went on to defeat Argentina in the final; Brazil achieved bronze.

